INSERT INTO `tbl_web_aboutus` (`id`, `title`, `content`, `photo_one`, `created_by`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(1, 'Slide 1', '<p>For the past two years, farmers have been constantly asking the question of what is Soil Charger technology which is constantly compelling the pomegranate farmers across the country, including Maharashtra, to answer their questions in one word is not possible . Because of the use of this technology, the positive changes between soil and crop and the humans and animals who use it as food are revolutionizing agriculture and human life. It has been undergoing innovative research worldwide for over 6000 years. Every day, new uses are coming up. It is a unique technology created by the Government of India under the new patent acquisition process. Which seeks to become the mainstay of prosperous and sustainable agriculture for the younger generation of farmers. Thousands of farmers have proven that agriculture can be sustainable and prosperous even today with the regular use of Soil Charger technology for four years, which is a golden opportunity for my young farming friends. In this, we are creating a platform for you and each other to guide free agriculture. With the help of information technology and agriculture experts, the latest changes in agriculture, along with the opportunity to market your own farm produce, come true, and we can achieve our dream and achieve it only with the collective efforts of all of us. our aim is sustainable and prosperous agriculture. Your mission is to have a career in a profitable farming.</p>\n', '1_companyprofile.png', 0, 1, '2021-07-10 06:14:55', '2021-10-06 11:07:34'),
(2, 'Slide 2', '<p>The main reason for the increase in agricultural production costs and incomes has been declining over the past few years, due to sudden change in environment, lack of effective alternatives to chemical fertilizers and medicines, due to its excessive use and hence poisoning of land, water and weeds result in crop diseases. . What is causing this is the decrease in soil fertility (humus / curb) i.e. organic carbon. You may be surprised to hear that the organic carbon in your soil in 1965 decreased from 3 to 4 percent To 0. 3 to 0. 4 percent today. In today&#39;s competition era, the use of chemical fertilizers, drugs and water is making it difficult to make agriculture in the race to generate more income. With the idea that millions of young people have a dream to make a profitable career with in farming, the time has come for the youngsters to become a helping hand and the birth of Soil Charger technology.</p>\n', '2_companyprofile.png', 0, 1, '2021-07-10 07:12:32', '2021-10-06 11:07:25'),
(4, 'owner speak', '<p>Ram Mukhekar, through his organisation Soil Charger Technology aims at healthy and tension free farming. Through his experiements, observations and studies, he is clear about soil organic carbon, soil fertility and soil health.</p>\n\n<p>Today, he also educates and trains farmers to grow safe, healthy and nutritous food, scientific reasons of treatment, natural farming practices. To him organic carbon is the soul of soil fertility.</p>\n\n<p>In our talk with him, he expresses the importance of organic carbon role into farming. He has developed high-tech resources for organic carbon and reach organic minerals by organic and ancent vedic methods into Soil Charger Technology.</p>\n\n<p><strong>How did you choose to be part of the agricultural industry ?</strong><br />\nBasically I am a farmer and started my agricultural journey from my childhood days and my father was my first teacher. We used to cultivate grains and vegetables since childhood. In my childhood days I have seen my father using chemicals on the farm. I have experienced and seen the effects of chemical farming. During the first 4-5 years the yield was tremendous. But gradually,in next 5-6years because of excessive use of chemical fertilisers and pesticides our yield began falling and we started facing a lot of deteriorating issues.</p>\n\n<p>At that time, I joined many agricultural seminars in our area and visited many exhibitions etc. In 2003, I started a farm of onions with the natural farming methodology. From 2003 - 2010, I imbibed a lot from natural and organic farming. I realised the advantages and disadvantages of the method. I got to try my hands on many new applications and techniques. I began sharing my thoughts and began guiding the farmers on my farm. This gradually turned into organizing meetings through which I could guide more farmers and bring positive changes to their ways of working. This way I got to hear their experiences too. 2012-2013 saw a huge blight attack in our vicinity. There was tremendous agricultural loss at the time. It was a difficult time for all of us.</p>\n\n<p><strong>When did you begin pomegranate cultivation?</strong><br />\nI was introduced to pomegranate farming 8 years ago.<br />\nIn 2013, I began my pomegranate garden but my finances were in loss. To irrigate my pomegranate farm, I used the same drips I used to irrigate my onion farm. That year, I just began with a single line of plants. I simply supplied the plants with nothing other than water and organic manure. I treated my pomegranate garden just the way I treated my onion garden. The roots developed well and everything was good but I only got a 6kg yield per plant the first year.</p>\n\n<p>In the second year, I wanted to increase the input I provided to my garden and so I used more organic resources like uric acid, seaweed extract etc. I used all possible organic products I could get hold of from the market. That year, I also tweaked my drip irrigation system a little. I gave a two lane drip irrigation on both sides of the plant row. I also used fertilizers on both sides of the plant row. That year I got 10 kg per plant. But during harvest, I realised I am not supplying the crop to the fullest.</p>\n\n<p>I got in touch with a few scientists I could get hold of and began focusing on residue free farming rather than natural farming. This method encourages us to use chemicals in mild amounts. It also encourages mulching, protecting the bio diversity of the soil and keeping away from plant growth hormones. This methodology was about taking the best of all farming methodologies. I was also careful not to disturb the soil as much as I could.</p>\n\n<p>I kept away from using herbicides and have not been using it since then. Herbicides disturbs the ecosystem, the bio diversity of the soil etc. That year, I also realized that in pomegranate plants, the fruit size is directly proportional to the leaf size. We need to take care of the soil tremendously because the health of the soil directly affects the root of the plant. The root development directly affects the leaf development, which in turn impacts the fruit development. If your leaf glows so will your fruit.</p>\n\n<p>During photosynthesis, the plant produces carbohydrates, starch and sugar. It also converts proteins, enzymes, stimulants, hormones etc. This teaches us plant metabolism and makes it clear that plant needs nourishment. We need to nourish the soil with organic carbon. To get healthy fruits, keep the canopy nourished.</p>\n\n<p><strong>What quantity of chemical fertilizers are we talking about?</strong><br />\nFor 520 plants, I used just 200kg chemical fertilizers. Also, I never used water solubles till date because I know how it depletes your soil off organic matter. It is acid based and so it burns all your soil carbon ripping it off its water holding capacity. Hence we used a lot of organic minerals.</p>\n\n<p>We manufactured a type of organic fertilizer which provides all 16 types of minerals like calcium, magnesium, sulphur, etc. For example, we use various types of cakes for npk , tobacco dust for nematode control, potash resource, rice bran for silicon resource, bonemeal as phosporous resource etc. It is all mixed and the mixture is composted for about 6-7 months and used to culture the soil. I am glad to say that year we got a production of 25kg fruits.</p>\n\n<p>We had continuous rain for 22 days that year. During that time, I didn&#39;t spray any kind of chemical fungicides. I only used Trichoderma and the fruit quality was excellent. Depriving our farm from pesticides etc, did not harm our crop in any manner.</p>\n\n<p>I have been following the same practices ever since the third year of my pomegranate cultivation.</p>\n\n<p>Although we use marginal chemical fertilizers, we have birds nests and honey in our garden and we get record-breaking yield of 70-100kg on a regular basis.</p>\n\n<p>Today more than 50,000 farmers farm along with me using these methods. I have many farmers visiting my garden.</p>\n\n<p><strong>So you recommend a mix of natural and chemicals, is it?</strong></p>\n\n<ol>\n	<li>100% natural farming is not great for hybrid cultivation. It needs mild amounts of chemical farming. Because for more growth hybrid varieties cosume more amount of minerals. If we blend 80 : 20 formula rich organic plus chemical, it turns into organic form with no harm for soil microbes and fertility.</li>\n	<li>The basic concept of natural farming is that the soil should have more than 10% organic carbon which is a reality only in the forest areas. This is due to large amount of natural mulching that happens in forests. But we harvest the produce and so we need to replace what we take from the garden.</li>\n	<li>All microbes are dependent on humus for food, which in turn is dependent on microbes for compost. Organic and biological sources together makes up for organic farming. We need to utilize this to our advantage.</li>\n	<li>Insead of providing microorganisms culture into soil I prefer provide rich source of organic carbon in to soil ,which is food of all friendly microbes.</li>\n	<li>Positive and rich in organic carbon resources boost friendly fungi and bacteria. Other side synthetic and chemical resourses increase power of pathogenic microbes . Hence health and disease microbes development is in total control of which types of food we provides through soil feedind.</li>\n	<li>That&rsquo;s why Our slogun is&nbsp;<strong>&ldquo;mitti balwan , fasal pahalwan , kisan dhanwan !!&rdquo;</strong></li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Our goal should be to produce poison-free nutritious food and that can be achieved by providing moderate amounts of organic and chemical fertilizers to the soil owing to the fact that hybrid varieties need more nourishment.</p>\n\n<p>Also, if we insist on only using organic resources, it will prove more expensive. We should remember that chemical fertilizers have maximum percentage of minerals. If we mix it with organic matter with 80:20 ratio and use it on the field, it gives the soil the nourishment it needs.</p>\n\n<p>I had so many doubts about the different kinds of inputs and ended up taking a course at one of the institutes and they also permit use of mild amounts of chemicals. However, they advised prohibition of all chemical pesticides and fungicides. I gradually cut down all the chemical pesticides and fungicides.</p>\n\n<p>Pomegranate is not a vegetable or a grain. When we cultivate a horticulture crop, the soil should be dominated with fungus. That is preferable for horticulture crops. Bacteria dominated soil is preferable for vegetables. But in organic farming the same jeevamrutha is being used for all kinds of crops. This hardly helps for fruit production. It is great for vegetables. When your soil is rich in bacteria, the nitrogen synthesis will increase vegetative growth which is favorable for all diseases that can attack pomegranates. So,100% organic farming can go against the physiology of hybrid pomegranates. Hence, residue free farming is the best methodology in today&#39;s conditions. Also, keep self study and awareness on high priority.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Have you used organic preparations like jeevamruth, amruth paani, etc?</strong><br />\nWe need to understand what these inputs do to the soil. Jevaamruth gives energy to the microbes. When we provide these biological cultures to the soil, it doesn&#39;t provide food for the soil or soil food web. which means these preparations are partialy useful. Microbes are very important to the soil no doubt. But it should develop as a result of nourished soil. Also, it is not sustainable and hence the instruction to repeat this every 7 days etc. This is because the soil inherently doesn&#39;t support these inputs. Whereas, if you provide organic carbon into the soil, automatically microbes increase.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Is it is better to use cow dung and compost which will provide more organic carbon to the soil?</strong><br />\nThe important question is if we are checking the organic carbon in the cow dung before incorporating into the soil. Nobody does it, right?</p>\n\n<p>If you do a test, you will find that there are lot of antibiotics in today&#39;s cow dung. Then, how will it increase the organic carbon content of the soil? In olden days, our cows used to graze in the forests etc. eating various types of grass etc. Desi cows gave powerful organic carbon rich cow dung. Now, such resources are hard to get. Cows are bound in the sheds and not allowed to graze naturally. If the cow is depleted from rich source of nutrition, how can they give rich dung?</p>\n\n<p>Adding one more point into it, which grasses we are feeding to cows is all hybrid varieties which has only vegetative growth. there stalks are almost empty from inside. How can it will nourish cattles health.</p>\n\n<p><strong>What is your opinion about zero budget organic farming?</strong><br />\nSometimes, I wonder how farmers can follow something without studying about it scientifically. Any forest requires fungus dominated soil. The ratio between bacteria and fungus should be 1:100 or at least 1:50. 1:1 ratio only results in grassland. A slight increase in this ratio will lead to vegetable growth. Bacteria dominated soil can rear grass and vegetables in rich quantities. When fungal ratio goes up you get more productive growth. Jivamruta will increases bacterial count hence it will boost nitrogen synthesis and vegetative growth and disease sensitivity of crop.</p>\n\n<p><strong>How much time will it take to decompose a ton of the mixture you recommend?</strong><br />\nWe are composting this outside our farm. We create layers and spray it with bacterial culture to aid decomposition. We then keep it for 6-7 months and use it as per requirement. When we cook food at high temperatures we are letting go of its nutritive value. This is a known fact. On the other hand, if we cook our food at moderate temperatures, we can preserve the nutritional value as well. Similarly, when you compost at a slow rate, organic carbon gets preserved. Using decomposition catalyzers to speed up the process will deprive the OC &amp; nutritional value of the compost.</p>\n\n<p><strong>What is the C:N ratio of this material and that of your soil?</strong><br />\nIt is 20:1 for the material and at the root zone of my soil the C:N ratio is approximately 30:1. Our organic carbon count is 2.5 right now.</p>\n\n<p><strong>We often see that the nutrients poured into the soil is not absorbed by the plant.</strong><br />\nWhen we maintain every nutrient artificially, one chemical molecule will always dominate other molecules. When magnesium increases, calcium falls low. So, you have keep testing your soil for what is deficient and keep feeding it. This is costly business for farmers.</p>\n\n<p>On the other hand, if we choose to nourish the soil, that is supply maximum amount of organic matter, clay particles, etc. These are all negatively charged. Our minerals are positively charged. Rich in organic carbon soil will boost soil food wed which will organise all mineral requirements of plant.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Do you use saplings or seeds to plant your pomegranate trees?</strong><br />\nWe use sapling method for pomegranates. There are two types of saplings - tissue culture and grafting. In our experience grafting is a better option for long-term farming. It is also disease resistance as compare to tissue.</p>\n\n<p><strong>How long does it take to get your first harvest?</strong><br />\nWithin 1-2 months, flowering happens but we don&#39;t let it happen so soon so that it&#39;s physical growth is not affected. So, the minimum requirement is 24 months. If you give the plant maximum time to grow and then get the production, you can have a sustainable model.</p>\n\n<p><strong>At what time of the year does the harvest happen?</strong><br />\nThere are three type of Bahar treatments (flower regulation) - Mrig bahar starting in June, Hasts Bahar beginning in Aug-Sept and Ambia Bahar which commences in March - April. Now, things depend on the area where you are cultivating. For instance in the Himachal they have only Mrig Bahar because the climatic conditions forses it. In Maharashtra there is a possibility of all three Bahars the safest of which is Ambia Bahar. Hast Bahar is also good but it rains a lot at that time. In Rajasthan they can go for Hasth Bahar. So, depending on the area of cultivation, you have three different seasons for possible harvest.</p>\n\n<p>For better crop yield pomegranate plant required two things, first is storage (bend plant refil sticks in 360 angle without breaking) into stalks and second is stress.(stop water and leaf will turn yellow)</p>\n\n<p><strong>What spacing do you suggest between pomegranate trees?</strong><br />\nThat depends on how you plan your cultivation. If you plan on cultivating your farm, for 15-20 years, the spacing should be 10ftx14ft. On an average on a one acre land, people plant around 400 plants. In South India, it is usually 350 plants. In Gujarat it is 450. But on an average it is 400 plants on an acre of land with a spacing of 8ftX12ft.</p>\n\n<p><strong>What is the life of a pomegranate tree?</strong><br />\nThis depends on the nourishment level of your soil. My garden has been around for 35 years in Maharashtra which we are using our technology. On an average, the plant will go on for 10-15years but if you are good with soil management and plant health it will go on to 30-40 years.</p>\n\n<p>In general farmers feed lesser than plant required. year by year Hence every year plant looses its physical health. Stem becomes weaker stem borer pin hole borer and wilting happens.</p>\n\n<p><strong>What is the yield per tree every year?</strong><br />\nIn the first year you get 10-15kg. From the second year onword if we nourish plant well the production should increase by 5kg pr plant every year.</p>\n\n<p><strong>I have read that pomegranate plant attracts a certain virus which destroys lot of crops. What do you do to counter it?</strong><br />\nThe pomegranate itself is an antioxidant. It is true that viruses can get attracted to pomegranate. But, not in a harmful manner. It is not true that if you have pomegranate, all other plants will get destroyed. The important thing is nourishing your soil because ill nourished soil will give rise to ill plants.</p>\n\n<p>Simply understand the fact.</p>\n\n<p>&ldquo;Weakness&rdquo; produces &ldquo;disease!!&rdquo;</p>\n\n<p>Everyone knows Weakness is resone for disease then why all farmers are expending energy and money on disease control !! why not for recover the weakness?</p>\n\n<p>In my point of view and experience of thousands of our follower farmers &ldquo;Farming is very easy. If we follow right way. Otherwise it will disaster what farmers are facing. I am very happy that we give confidence to thousand of farmers</p>\n\n<p>in pomegranate, who are at the age of cutting off plans due to bacterial blight and wilt.</p>\n\n<p>Thx a lot!!</p>\n\n<p>Ram mukhekar.</p>\n\n<p>Founder of Soil charger technology</p>\n\n<p>Nashik. 3feb 2021</p>\n', '4_companyprofile.png', 0, 1, '2021-07-28 08:44:10', '2021-10-06 11:07:11'),
(5, 'Mr. Ram Mukhekar ', '<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong><span style=\"color:black\">Friends,<br />\nAfter the Green Revolution, humans, out of a desire for higher income, interfered with the natural life&nbsp;cycle of crops and overused entrepreneurs and chemicals. As a result, the health of crop and soil&nbsp;was endangered. Recognizing this threat in 2015, SCT gave first priority to increase soil fertility and organic carbon. Its first objective was to provide a strong source of organic carbon.</span></strong></span></p>\n\n<p><br />\n<span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong><span style=\"color:black\">Gradually realizing the importance of organic carbon, SCT has worked to alleviate the prosperity of farmers. Soil pollution stopped by&nbsp;providing strong alternatives.</span></strong></span></p>\n\n<p><br />\n<span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong><span style=\"color:black\">The 3rd step is to stop the use of synthetic PGR&nbsp;and provide a safe alternative to the&nbsp;development of natural hormones in crops with the help of Mycorrhiza.</span></strong></span></p>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong><span style=\"color:black\">The 4th step is to stop the flow of toxic pollutants in the name of crop protection.&nbsp;Although thousands of farmers have shown from their experience that nutrition is the only option for&nbsp;crop protection, the management of SCT Saptapadi was born in 2021 after some farmers made&nbsp;management mistakes.</span></strong></span></p>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong><span style=\"color:black\">The journey of Vedic from SCT.&nbsp;From 2015-19, it was impossible to satisfy his appetite&nbsp;using only SCT, so he had to relay on chemical fertilizers. Vedic Scientists, myself &amp;&nbsp;team have come up with 10&nbsp;years of research and Vedic&nbsp;technology has been born through the teachings of SCT and Vedic.</span></strong></span></p>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong><span style=\"color:black\">Today, the SCT Vedic will be a revolutionary step in the Indian agricultural sector as India&nbsp;becomes a superpower in the 21st century. We have faith in agriculture and soil to&nbsp;complete farmers dream. </span></strong></span>​​​​​​</p>\n', 'ram_sir.png', 0, 0, '2021-10-06 13:02:55', '2023-12-18 12:34:26'),
